name: 3-chloro-4-(trifluoromethoxy)benzonitrile
Reason: The compound 3-chloro-4-(trifluoromethoxy)benzonitrile consists of a benzene ring which has a base melting point, multiple substituents that influence the melting point: a cyano group (C#N), a chloro group (Cl), and a trifluoromethoxy group (OCF3). Here is how each group affects the base melting point: Benzene base melting point: 5.5 C. Chloro group: -15 C (halogens like chlorine generally decrease the melting point due to their size and mass disrupting the crystal lattice structure). Cyano group (C#N): +20 C (cyano groups increase melting point due to their electronegativity and ability to form dipoles that increase intermolecular forces). Trifluoromethoxy group (OCF3): +30 C (trifluoromethyl groups increase the melting point because of the strong dipole-dipole interactions due to the highly electronegative fluorine atoms). Combining these effects, the prediction for the melting point can be made.
